<h3 id="overview">Overview</h3>
<p>
    <code>CustomSerializer</code> is the single contract every serializer flavor implements:
    <code>serialize(model)</code> &rarr; string and <code>deserialize(string)</code> &rarr; model, round-tripping the
    structured content pivot to and from a wire format. The platform-default <strong>HTML flavor</strong> (the default a
    project config extends) and every alternative flavor (Markdown, JSON node-tree, …) satisfy this same interface,
    which is what lets <a href="/plugs/customserializerregistry/">the registry</a> treat them interchangeably.
</p>

<h3 id="standards">Web Standards Alignment</h3>
<we-data-table><table>
    <tr><th>Standard</th><th>Status</th><th>How We Adopt It</th></tr>
    <tr>
        <td><a href="https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/HTML">HTML</a></td>
        <td>Baseline</td>
        <td>The default flavor's wire format is sanitized HTML.</td>
    </tr>
</table></we-data-table>

<h3 id="interface">Interface</h3>
{% highlight "typescript" %}
interface CustomSerializer {
    /** Structured content model → wire string (e.g. HTML, Markdown). */
    serialize(model: ContentModel): string;
    /** Wire string → structured content model (inverse of serialize). */
    deserialize(wire: string): ContentModel;
}
{% endhighlight %}

<p class="text-sm text-gray-600 mt-4">
    Satisfied alike by the HTML-flavor platform default and by every alternative flavor registered through the
    <a href="/plugs/customserializerregistry/"><code>CustomSerializerRegistry</code></a>.
    See <a href="/projects/webediting/">Web Editing</a>.
</p>
